Following on from the 3.0 issue #280.  This is the config parser.

It is a basic top down parser.

We break the config into a list of tokens and travel through them to build
up a dict that corresponds to the config.

The parser allows:

* containers
```
    container {
        included_module 1 {}
        included_module 2 {}
    }
```
* nesting of containers
```
    container 1 {
        container 2 {
            included_module 1 {}
        }
        included_module 2 {}
    }
```
* many types including lists, dict and tuple values
```
    my_module {
        my_str = 'hello'
        my_int = 23
        my_bool = true
        my_list = [1, 2, 3]
        my_dict = {'x': 1, 'y': 2}
        my_tuple = (1, 'something')
        my_complex = {
            'list' : [1, 2, 3],
            'dict' : {'x': 1, 'y': 2}
        }
    }
```

We can cope with horrible stuff all on one line which I do not condone
```
group tz { cycle = 0 open = false volume_status { button_up = 4 button_down = 5 button_mute = 0 } time {} tztime la { format = "LA %H:%M:%S" timezone = "America/Los_Angeles" } tztime ny { format = "NY %H:%M:%S" timezone = "America/New_York" } tztime du { format = "DU %H:%M:%S" timezone = "Asia/Dubai" } }
```

If an error is detected we:

* Inform the user about the error as best we can

```
general {{
        colors = false
}
CONFIG ERROR: Name expected saw `{` at line 1 position 9
```

Any module can declare itself as a container via our old friend class Meta
```
    class Meta:
        container = True
```

We try to cope with the config as well as we can.  If things are too bad we use a special error config so we can start and show the error in the status bar.


The process is two stage

1) parse the config into a general dict

2) parse that dict into a py3status config 

Hopefully having the two split helps.

To see the output as py3status gets it run `python parse_config.py <path-to-config>` in no config we try `~/.i3/i3status.conf`


I am aware of a few issues where the old parser accepted things eg
```
general {
        colors = false
}}
CONFIG ERROR: Name expected saw `}` at line 3 position 2
```
the old parser would be fine here.  As we get useful error that tell us the line/char and some basic issue, this should not be a major issue for users.

~~`i3status.py` changes include the  PR write_tmp_i3status_config() rewrite #248 which makes things look more complicated than they are.~~

Anyhow it's here and I suspect it will need time to be assessed.  I will try to add a few more comments/docstrings especially around the processing for py3status `process_config()`

Please try to break it.

Closes #68 (unless I've misunderstood!)

Follows on from #116.

@EntilZha, please see what you think.

## Goals

* Add a boundary field for all the models that might have boundaries;
* Add a mechanism to import boundary/GIS data to the correct places;

## Considerations

1. The boundary field is nullable and of type MultiPolygon, to accurately represent data that have islands, such as Japan, that is made up of multiple parts;
1. The boundary field was added to ```Place``` model, so all inheritors have the field as well.

## What's done so far

1. Fields added to the models;
1. Changed from ROOT_URLCONF ```test_project.urls``` to ```test_app.urls``` - when trying to migrate the test_app would not find ```test_project.urls```, so this is kinda of a fix;
1. Changed ```WSGI_APPLICATION``` from ```test_project.wsgi.application``` to ```test_app.wsgi.application```. Also kinda of a fix.

## What needs to be done

1. Determine the best source for GIS data;
1. Change the import command so it can handle boundary data;

For our project, we need to make such a setting work:

```'session': {
  'default_timeout': 100,
  'default_fetch_size': None
}```

Since it did not work, played with code to figure out that we need to manually assign this to the session. This commit is a working change.

A bit of profiling and research lead me to try the performance test suggested in #2739 for Perl.  The performance test code
```perl
#!/usr/bin/perl
use strict;
use warnings;
use AI::MXNet 'mx';
use Benchmark;

my $a = mx->random->normal(0, 1, [ 4, 1024, 1024 ]);
mx->nd->waitall();

my $p = $a->aspdl;
my $size = length(${$p->get_dataref}) / 2 ** 30;

my $t = Benchmark::countit(-4, sub { $a->aspdl });
printf("GB/s: %g\n", $t->iters * $size / $t->[0]);
```
gave me `GB/s: 0.851562` on master.  after looking into the code a bit, this patch brings the performance test to `GB/s: 8.35156` due to reduced buffer copying overhead.

